00:07:47.040 --> 00:07:48.650
Now if I could do just
one thing today,

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:53.060
that would be to really
impart upon you a basic idea.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:07:56.600
And that is that Persian
literary history as written,

00:07:56.600 --> 00:07:58.360
particularly when it
comes to the 18th

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:01.740
and 19th Century is insufficient.

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:04.580
It's insufficient because in
the 18th and 19th Century,

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:08.600
Persian literary writing is
unable to account for trends

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:12.230
and multiple literary phenomena
occurring outside of Iran.

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:16.020
So Persia was this great,
prevalent, prodigious social,

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:20.360
linguistic cultural idiom that
connected Sufis travelers,

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:24.850
[inaudible] and Sultans from
Anatolia to Western China.

00:08:24.850 --> 00:08:27.040
And we hear about this
in the development

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:29.010
of Persian literary history
but suddenly in the 18th

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:32.670
and 19th Century, we lose these
kinds of trends regional scope

00:08:32.670 --> 00:08:35.820
and suddenly the story of
Persian literary history becomes

00:08:35.820 --> 00:08:37.260
Iran's story.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:39.310
And to put it more bluntly,
Persian literary history

00:08:39.310 --> 00:08:42.840
at this period is Iranian
literary history.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:45.980
So Persian literary history
has been infused with some kind

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.960
of national sentimentality
stemming from Iran.

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:53.770
And I think actually we
can pinpoint the idea,

00:08:53.770 --> 00:08:55.390
the point at which this idea

00:08:55.390 --> 00:08:58.830
of Iranian nationalists
sentimentality interjected

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:02.160
or intervened in the writing
of Persian literary history

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:06.500 position:56%
and that's an idea that's called
Bazgasht-i Adabi or Literary Return.

00:09:06.500 --> 00:09:09.860
And I'll talk about in more detail
in a moment, but I just wanted

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:12.850 position:56%
to kind of mention this because it's
a framework I'm working with today

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:15.010
and also kind of working against.

00:09:15.010 --> 00:09:18.910
And this idea is that in
the 18th and 19th Century,

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:22.830
Iranian poets rescued Persian
poetry from despair by returning

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:24.270
to the styles of the Masters.

00:09:24.270 --> 00:09:27.690
So they returned to the styles
of the classical Masters

00:09:27.690 --> 00:09:30.440
that were prevalent to the
9th and the 15th Century.

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:33.180
They returned to their
glorious and simple prose.

00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:36.900
And they did so by moving away
from this stagnant literary style

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.710
that we're told was
occurring and being written

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:44.140
and produced throughout Central
and South Asia and elsewhere

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:46.570
but crucially not in Iran.

00:09:46.570 --> 00:09:49.940
So there it is, Iranian poets
in the 18th and 19th Century,

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:52.120
they somehow divide
themselves, they reconnect

00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:55.550
with the Masters while
others elsewhere do not.

00:09:55.550 --> 00:10:01.100
They remain kind of stagnating in
this decadent literary culture.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:04.560
Now there's some major impacts of
this idea, there's a lot of kind

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:08.740
of historiographical
debris in its wake.

00:10:08.740 --> 00:10:11.270
One thing I already alluded to
was the conflation of Iranian

00:10:11.270 --> 00:10:12.840
and Persian literary history.

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:14.480
I mean suddenly the
story in the 18th

00:10:14.480 --> 00:10:19.300
and 19th Century is not this kind
of cosmopolitan macro level view

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:20.600
of Persian literary history.

00:10:20.600 --> 00:10:26.160
But it's focusing slowly or
exclusively rather on Iran.

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:28.130
The second thing that happens is

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:31.920
that there's a greater proprietary
right over the Masters in Iran.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:37.430
So these great Masters like Rumi,
Hafiz, Ferdowsi who were productive

00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:42.760
in the 9th to 15th Century are
the ones in which Iranian poets

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:45.950
and only Iranian poets
are reconnecting with.

00:10:45.950 --> 00:10:48.490
And so if we're told that
Iranian poets are reconnecting

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:53.090
with are re-finding these
Masters while others are not,

00:10:53.090 --> 00:10:54.390
well that asserts a kind

00:10:54.390 --> 00:10:59.460
of more proprietary right
by Iran at this time.

00:10:59.460 --> 00:11:01.970
The second, the third
thing rather it does it

00:11:01.970 --> 00:11:04.940
that it erases other facets
of Persian literary culture.

00:11:04.940 --> 00:11:07.930 position:56%
I mean again, we're told by this
narrative that the important element

00:11:07.930 --> 00:11:10.940
of Persian literary history in
the 18th and 19th Century is

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:12.870
that these few Iranian
poets connected

00:11:12.870 --> 00:11:17.820
with the Masters while the rest of
the world kind of remains decadent

00:11:17.820 --> 00:11:19.930
in their negative literary ways.

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:21.630
And so again, that
erases a lot of kind

00:11:21.630 --> 00:11:25.010
of multiple literary phenomena
occurring at the time.

00:11:25.010 --> 00:11:27.050
And towards the end of my
talk, I'll point other things

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:30.660
that are happening around
this time outside of Iran

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:35.040
which I think are a
integral part of this story.

00:11:35.040 --> 00:11:38.660
So I'm going to break my
talk into three parts.

00:11:38.660 --> 00:11:41.880
First I'll at how this narrative
of return Bazgasht became

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:45.580
to be fashion, what it entails,
